    "summary": "The Silla Unification of Korea (668 AD) was the first political unification of the Korean Peninsula, achieved when the kingdom of Silla — the smallest and initially weakest of the [[event:2091|Three Kingdoms of Korea]] — allied with the Tang Dynasty of China to conquer Baekje (660 AD) and Goguryeo (668 AD), then successfully resisted Chinese attempts to absorb the peninsula into the Tang Empire directly. The resulting United Silla state (668–935 AD) governed the Korean Peninsula south of the Taedong River, establishing political unity that (with interruptions) has characterized Korea ever since.\n\nThe United Silla period was a golden age of Korean culture, particularly Buddhist art and architecture. The Bulguksa Temple complex (751 AD) near the Silla capital Gyeongju, with its paired stone pagodas (Dabotap and Seokgatap), represents the apex of Korean Buddhist architecture. The Seokguram grotto (c. 774 AD), housing a monumental granite Buddha overlooking the sea, is considered one of East Asia's greatest sculptural achievements. Gyeongju (then called Seorabeol) was one of the largest cities in the world at the time, and Korean Buddhist scholarship — building on the [[event:2095|Three Kingdoms tradition]] — produced important theological syntheses. The Silla state eventually fragmented in the late 9th century under pressure from local strongmen and revolts, leading to the later Goryeo unification in 918–936 AD.",
